<subSubSection id="FB85A611ED76214DA6A3B803D3ACBB68" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="12EC8074411536E87F74549DDC5ACC01" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6E00E8EF24A5BB93C3EC754C266B0714" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
This Old World species is naturalized throughout temperate regions of the New World. The species was already widespread in Mexico by the mid-1800's: Popocatepetl, 
<emphasis id="6E3C4FEAD5BB2E3346E4CC679FA7F723" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">H.G. Galeotti 5828</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="F0A192B386BDB4F0258BFAE825B0B658" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">5854</emphasis>
(US fragm. ex CAEN in 1837-1847); Orizaba, 
<emphasis id="7EE3C6DAEE303800035803B73A47E44A" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
F. 
<normalizedToken id="F8A62C84AA5266F4430CDE11ABDD6EF9" originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
2094
</emphasis>
(US fragm. ex P in the 1850's); and San Luis 
<normalizedToken id="64F9FA2DAF91B09A11DAE30383F86A2A" originalValue="Potosí">Potosi</normalizedToken>
, 
<emphasis id="07B11C9D82D23266E50A8D8CA02AC312" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
M. 
<normalizedToken id="73833B0491BF9270A56D791425BC7EC4" originalValue="Virlet-d’Aoust">Virlet-d'Aoust</normalizedToken>
1372
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="3C19045E20BEACA875CE9630DEFCD766" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">1394</emphasis>
(US fragm. ex P in 1851). Above we list a single specimen per state for this species, except when there is notable morphological variation. We cite the oldest voucher seen that came from the state. The species probably occurs sporadically in additional states and is surely in Sinaloa but without a collection. Plants from wet areas at high altitudes can perenniate by rooting at the nodes (noted in specimens cited from 
<normalizedToken id="D7A14363DABD671D44C8A5EF0420BDAD" originalValue="Michoacán">Michoacan</normalizedToken>
and Puebla), and such forms have been called 
<taxonomicName id="9134BBE4C40989284A0D9D373E1C83BE" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annua">
<emphasis id="BC257A745A187EF111D924E356CB64C1" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa annua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
var. 
<emphasis id="10BCADC5270608D7B4708EA69F9D5E36" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">reptans</emphasis>
Hausskn. We suspect that such forms arise repeatedly in plastic response to the environmental conditions, rather than from unique genetic variation, and are not particularly useful to recognize taxonomically. A form with the lemmas and paleas glabrous or nearly glabrous occurs sporadically around the world, and has been found in Guerrero. All collections from Mexico we have seen identified as &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="3098EE582392994C1F37C62695EA56DA" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="265FF06197A69603C59440A82EE851CA" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; belong to 
<taxonomicName id="C0641CE13F9903748632854DF8D84C80" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annua">
<emphasis id="0F59374BEC443EED38BB1676AED80F23" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa annua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and only one specimen was redetermined by us as 
<taxonomicName id="FAF774D65863C7AB16695412195E6AD7" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="E93DD8337C88F8564B26F64B77B9B581" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from among hundreds of 
<taxonomicName id="827DB286A251682906239B5B78A3D565" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annua">
<emphasis id="30445E2567854FBB7C70260EADBF35D3" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa annua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens. DNA data support the hypothesis that 
<taxonomicName id="0F28225F15AD6BFD56D7805FF7BE311F" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annua">
<emphasis id="D6956FB3FDDA03DB7222046A66717468" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa annua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a tetraploid species, arose from hybridization between two Eurasian diploid species, 
<taxonomicName id="645C4E68EF9E4D5441EA8D73B9DDFA8E" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="651402B15276C1B3EBEC9641097BE331" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="2AD26401BFC2E8572370AF4DFEFBE68E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
<emphasis id="2F3240B0BFFB635277219C16CC6A6709" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">supina</emphasis>
Schrad. (
<bibRefCitation id="356A3EEF983FD01889286D4B19CBF58B" author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Madrono" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="B52" refString="Soreng, RJ, Bull, RD, Gillespie, LJ, 2010. Phylogeny and reticulation in Poa L. based on plastid trnTLF and nrITS sequences with attention to diploids. In: Seberg O, Petersen G, Barfod AS, Davis JI (Eds) Diversity, Phylogeny, and Evolution in the Monocotyledons, Aarhus University Press, Aarhus, 619-643." title="Phylogeny and reticulation in Poa L. based on plastid trnTLF and nrITS sequences with attention to diploids. In: Seberg O, Petersen G, Barfod AS, Davis JI (Eds) Diversity, Phylogeny, and Evolution in the Monocotyledons, Aarhus University Press, Aarhus, 619 - 643." year="2010">Soreng et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="E2C8836A7EE07DE4240E3DB353DE438F" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="62C8B11FD3C9CD873A78146ACA407527" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a short-lived annual and 
<taxonomicName id="38CB7890BD5C444B02CC3EBBC54DED9A" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="supina">
<emphasis id="FCF27E2D4FADC957730F500B77F8958F" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Poa supina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a stoloniferous 
<pageBreakToken id="ECEEE958333476547BB6FD5E76E9B7A1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" start="start">perennial</pageBreakToken>
. Species of this complex [
<taxonomicName id="EE0044AFFD9F32BE7779CF95060C05C0" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="98EE80A293A87271E010E357E1DBEEA4" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sect. 
<taxonomicName id="E15905CD997C167BF872A6DD93232502" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Micrantherae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="369522E90C7492FB5A95886F40FA0BB1" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Micrantherae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Stapf; syn. 
<taxonomicName id="B103C784A2E85DEA3BDE5E812CD10DFC" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="505447685BFBDF54CF75576963430668" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sect. 
<taxonomicName id="04D04F3EF96F617DD475A5FCD685EBA1" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ochlopoa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8EC103C4C9EF493EAE4119241157F750" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ochlopoa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Asch. &amp; Graebn., 
<taxonomicName id="524EEB10CE91F72FDC078A03FF56AD32" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ochlopoa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F1C5AE5D379057C53FDCFE667526DC91" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ochlopoa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Asch. &amp; Graebn.) H. Scholz.] have spikelets with perfect lower florets and pistillate upper florets, smooth branches and spikelet bracts, and soft puberulent lemma keels and marginal veins, soft puberulent palea keels, and glabrous calluses. 
<taxonomicName id="10BFBD85A1EC5AD1055992889CBA3845" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annua">
<emphasis id="F56E2C9C92E754751915A2C24E98AA52" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa annua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
frequently approaches 
<taxonomicName id="1A14CC15DC0DFA2227509AA1AA2867DD" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="D74CB176C81985F3B210CEECE49669A9" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in form, presumably in part due to expression of particular genes, or segregation of those genes toward the parental species. This hypothesis explains the difficulty of identifying true diploid 
<taxonomicName id="81EDE55DF8E0C1C21A56C7780E9C459A" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="254D612201F074E2DB68BF869382331F" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In a separate review of US New World specimens previously identified as 
<taxonomicName id="6B9BB3FD72C6C7F80105431C28FA29FA" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annua">
<emphasis id="FF1F8F064A7D781E0A1BF5601A0711C8" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa annua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="A82B9332DF4D72495519A052845DB0B0" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="B3158ACEDCDA0548B338D42A05511BED" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Hildemar Scholz (B, dets. of 2007), only one specimen from Central America was identified as other than 
<taxonomicName id="256DFA23EE9472E351A80C597544AE0A" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annua">
<emphasis id="9F9231C8B91F82B03054949DDDB04E4F" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa annua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<taxonomicName id="770692E43E463AE39394B399A0A49272" authorityName="Kunth, Nov. Gen. Sp. (quarto ed.) 1: 158. 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="infirma">
<emphasis id="81F6B9624B6C9782E5BC4F12F495F6F8" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Poa infirma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
discussion below).
</paragraph>
